    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "In diagram form, for folk who have trouble visualizing the depth coordinate system:\r\n\r\n![zscale](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/167819/45693980-31b00180-bb56-11e8-9521-f6aa648657c0.png)\r\n\r\nMost sprites (with ZScale: 0) are rendered parallel to the plane of the camera, as in the left hand case.  If they happen to be centered at a height of the ground level, then the bottom half of the sprite will clip behind the terrain and be hidden.\r\n\r\nSprites that line \"on\" the ground (ZScale: 1) are tilted back, with the z coordinate increasing at the same rate as the y coordinate, which matches the terrain.  A small offset (applied using the z coordinate on s.Offset) may be needed to push it back from the ground to prevent z-fighting.\r\n\r\nEdit: On second look, my z coordinate may be defined backwards here.  This would only affect the sign of the z-offset, and not the basic geometry.  The \"y\" and \"z\" are also really deltas, so should be considered as \"dY\" and \"dZ\".  That's what I get for doing too quick of a sketch."
  },
